**Segments**

- By Diagnosis (Mammography, Ultrasound, MRI)
- By Treatment (Medication, Surgery)

Mammary duct ectasia is a common condition in women approaching menopause and refers to the inflammation of the milk ducts behind the nipple. The market for mammary duct ectasia can be segmented based on the diagnosis and treatment methods used. In terms of diagnosis, the market is categorized into mammography, ultrasound, and MRI. Mammography is often utilized to detect any abnormalities in the breast tissues, while ultrasound is helpful in providing real-time imaging of the affected area. MRI, on the other hand, offers a detailed view of the breast tissue, aiding in accurate diagnosis. When it comes to treatment, options include medication and surgery. Medication is often prescribed to reduce inflammation and manage symptoms, while surgery may be required in severe cases to remove the affected duct.

